snig
Homonym Number: 1
Word Class:verb
Sense Number:
Definition:to drag (a load) along the ground. [British dialect]
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: bush-clearing, milling
Citations
Date: 0/0/1986
Source: Off the Sheep's Back
Author: RICHARDS
Vol / Page: 24
Edition:
Quote: Fortunately, there was a timber mill operating nearby. By borrowing horses, they were able to snig the timber home through the bush track.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 105
Edition:
Quote: <i>snig </i> to drag a heavy load with ropes and chains; originally logging word for dragging a log. <i>- snigged home </i> tied up, pulled into place, piled up, as in Frank S. Anthony's <i>Me and Gus </i>; Barry Crump in <i>Hang on a Minute, Mate</i> refers to a <i>snigging track </i>; origins obscure, Northern English dialect word. NZA.
Notes:

Date: 26/10/1881
Source: West Coast Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: The County Chairman was present at the meeting, and he ordered me to "snig" two logs about 30ft long and throw them over the gap in the bridge; when I went down I found that there was a gap of 56ft and that I could not get logs suitable for the purpose, as one set of logs had been carried away by the flood, and the other set was not fit to put stringers on.
Notes:

