Date: 2/12/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote:  To drag along the ground by horse or bullocks, especially to drag logs or other timber. The stout chain which goes round the log has a ring at one end, and a hook to which the horses' chains are attached. It is called a <i>snigging chain</i>. (C.)
Notes: Acland Glossary

